headline: Hershey beats quarterly estimates on strong Easter demand
summary: STORY: U.S. chocolate maker Hershey beat analysts' sales and profit estimates for the second quarter on Wednesday, driven by strong Easter demand for its sweets and steady growth for its salty snacks.Shares of the company rose as much as almost 7% in morning trading, but gave back some gains by midday.Hershey said sales volume rose about 21%, due to planned changes in its inventory and supply chain in the North America Confectionery and International segments.But U.S. President Donald Trump's tariffs are skyrocketing the cost of importing already-pricey cocoa and hurting the competitiveness of American factories.Hershey has estimated it could face up to $180 million in tariff costs this year.Under pressure from rising costs, earlier this month, Hershey rolled out double-digit price hikes across its confectionery products including Reese's cups to retailers like Walmart and Kroger.

headline: Dove, Walmart and Big Brothers Big Sisters of America Announce Back-to-School Partnership to Support Youth Mentorship and Confidence
summary: Beauty brand Dove - the world leader in self-esteem education - Big Brothers Big Sisters of America (BBBSA) and Walmart are teaming up for the first year of a multi-year partnership on a series of back-to-school events at select Walmart locations throughout August. The initiative includes community events designed to support youth mentorship and confidence as students head into the new school year, beginning with a First Friday event on Aug. 1 in Bentonville, AR.

headline: Amazon still the online retailer of choice as cloud business faces competition
summary: (Reuters) -Amazon will seek to reassure investors on Thursday that its cloud business, a critical driver of profits, is growing at a fast enough clip to offset any pullback in consumer spending that could throttle its retail operations.  Amazon Web Services (AWS), the cloud unit that accounts for less than a fifth of the company's sales but typically about 60% of its profit, likely grew 17% in the April-June period.  Amazon, like its rivals Alphabet and Microsoft, has invested heavily to increase capacity at its data centers to meet demand for its traditional cloud services as well as the surge in generative AI services.
